title: * The List of All Active Datasets in this ERDDAP *
summary: This dataset is a table which has a row of information for each dataset currently active in this ERDDAP.

title: 63rd St., Chicago, IL Weather Station
summary: The weather station at Jackson Park on 63rd St in Chicago, IL (USA) was established and is maintained by the Chicago Park District. The purpose is to provide real-time meteorological information to the public. The station measures temperature, winds, precipitation, and other weather parameters.

title: Algoma Panther Buoy
summary: ALGOMA is a seasonally deployed Panther buoy in Lake Michigan near Algoma, Wisconsin. It is equipped to measure water quality, as well as meteorological parameters, wave height and direction, and temperature throughout the water column. The buoy was built and is operated and maintained by University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.

title: Ashtabula water intake:water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. Between 2014 and 2018, LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant operated by Aqua America in Ashtabula,Ohio to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). A YSI EXO2 sonde is installed in the raw water intake pipe at the water treatment plant. In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system. This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

title: Atwater 20-meter buoy (ATW20) : meteorological and water quality data
summary: The Atwater 20-meter buoy (ATW20) is located approximately 2 km offshore of Milwaukee\u2019s Atwater Beach in Lake Michigan. A two-point mooring system secures the buoy over sand and rock substrate in 20 m of water. The buoy is equipped with a solar-powered weather station and water quality sensors that collect data every 30 min, as well as a vertical string of temperature sensors, a downward-looking current profiler, and a cellular modem for real-time data communication.

title: Bark Point, WI Moored Buoy
summary: University of Minnesota-Duluth started deploying moored buoy BARK_PT in southwest Lake Superior near Bark Point, Wisconsin in April 2021. Bark Point is a region that has recently started to experience noticeable algae blooms and there was a desire to monitor the area for water quality. Waves, water temperatures at depth, water quality (including turbidity, dissolved oxygen, chl-a and BGA fluorescence), and basic meteorological data are also collected at this site. BARK_PT is in 50 meters of water. This buoy is operated and maintained by University of Minnesota-Duluth Large Lakes Observatory with support from the Great Lakes Observing System.

title: Beach 2 Buoy
summary: The Beach 2 Buoy is a seasonal moored buoy deployed for measuring water conditions, including physical parameters, as well as water quality parameters. It is deployed off Beach 2 at Presque Isle State Park and is owned, maintained, and operated by the Regional Science Consortium.

title: Beach 2 Tower
summary: The Beach 2 Tower is a fixed tower used to measure a wide suite of meteorological parameters, including winds, precipitation, temperature, and barometric pressure. It is deployed on the dune line at Presque Isle State Park and is owned, maintained, and operated by the Regional Science Consortium.

title: Beach 6 Buoy

institution: Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians
title: Bliss Beach Weather Station
summary: This weather station is located at Bliss Beach in Bliss, Michigan. The weather station, owned and operated by the Little Traverse Bay Band of Odawa Indians, will gather more temporally robust, accurate, and precise measures of climatology to determine the effect of climatology on YOY Lake Whitefish recruitment, alert the public to hazardous conditions, and improve weather forecasts. Each year, the WS700 multi-parameter weather station will relay real-time information on wind speed and direction, air temperature, and other environmental characteristics such as: humidity, solar radiation, pressure, and precipitation.

title: Blue Water Bridge ABS
summary: This location measures sediment concentration from a single point in the river near the Blue Water Bridge on the American side. It is important to note the concentrations measured at this point DO NOT represent the average concentration in the entire cross section. This location is known to have a strong lateral concentration gradient. The purpose of the instrument is to provide an idea of when sediment is present in the water column and when it is not. This site is funded and maintaind by the US Army Corps of Engineers.

title: Bradford Beach Panther Buoy
summary: Bradford Beach buoy is a seasonally deployed buoy in Lake Michigan near Bradford Beach, Milwaukee, Wisconsin. It is equipped to measure water quaity including algal blooms, as well as meteorological parameters and water temperature. The buoy was built and is operated and maintained by University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.

title: Carrol Township:water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. Between 2014 and 2018, LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant system at Caroll Township to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system.This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

title: Chicago Pier Buoy
summary: 45198 is a seasonal moored buoy deployed near Chicago, Illinois, USA, about 1.3 miles off Navy Pier, and has been active since August 2021. The buoy is operated by Illinois Indiana Sea Grant and is maintained in partnership with Purdue University and LimnoTech.

title: City of Elyria:water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. Between 2014 and 2018, LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant system at City of Elyria to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system.This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

title: Cleveland DO Buoy
summary: Station 45164 is a seasonal moored buoy deployed in Lake Erie about 15 miles offshore of Cleveland, Ohio, in 75 feet of water. Known as Cleveland Water\u2019s Offshore buoy, it was originally deployed in 2010 through a USEPA Great Lakes Restorative Initiative grant administered by Great Lakes Observing System. The buoy is now maintained by Cleveland Water in partnership with Cleveland Water Alliance and LimnoTech. The buoy\u2019s purpose is to monitor water quality as well as meteorological and physical water parameters useful for providing water treatment, including tracking seasonal hypoxia in the Central Basin.

title: Cleveland Intake Crib Buoy
summary: Station 45176 is a seasonal moored buoy deployed in Lake Erie about 4 miles offshore of Cleveland, Ohio, in 50 feet of water. Known as Cleveland Water\u2019s Crib buoy, it was originally deployed in 2010 through a USEPA Great Lakes Restorative Initiative grant administered by Great Lakes Observing System. The buoy is now maintained by Cleveland Water in partnership with Cleveland Water Alliance and LimnoTech. The buoy\u2019s purpose is to monitor water quality as well as meteorological and physical water parameters useful for providing water treatment.

title: Cook Nuclear Plant Buoy(45026): meteorological and water station
summary: The Cook Nuclear Plant buoy(45026) was designed by the University of Michigan's Ocean Engineering Laboratory (OEL) and deployed in 2011 through a partnership with LimnoTech Inc. This buoy measures wind speed and direction, air and water temperature, relative humidity, wave direction, height and period. The data is logged internally as well as transmitted in ten minute intervals to the internet via cellular modem.

title: Copper Harbor Spotter
summary: Previously moored near Isle Royale in 2022, SPOT-1810 is is located 0.5 miles northwest of the entrance to Copper Harbor (MI) in Lake Superior. It measures surface wave parameters, surface temperature, and provides derived wind information. It is owned and operated by Michigan Technological University.

title: Copper Harbor Spotter
summary: Previously moored near Isle Royale in 2022, SPOT-1810 is is located 0.5 miles northwest of the entrance to Copper Harbor (MI) in Lake Superior. It measures surface wave parameters, surface temperature, and provides derived wind information. It is owned and operated by Michigan Technological University.

title: Copper Harbor Spotter Buoy
summary: This buoy is located 0.5 miles northwest of the entrance to Copper Harbor (MI) in Lake Superior. The buoy is owned by the University of Michigan's Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research while maintained and deployed by Michigan Technological University's Great Lakes Research Center to enhance safety for recreational stakeholders, while providing valuable realtime observations for Great Lakes researchers and forecasters. Each year from about May 1 to November 1, this Sofar Spotter buoy will measure wave height and wave period, as well as surface temperature every 30 minutes, reporting these values once per hour. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Defiance Water Treatment Plant Maumee River Monitoring Station
summary: The river sampling station is located inside the Defiance Water Treatment Plant's Pump House. Water is pumped from the Maumee River intake at the Water Plant up to a tank in the Pump House where NuLab sampling equipment and a YSI sonde perform various analysis on river water quality. That analysis is continuous and updated to the website continuously. The analysis will provide vital information to WTP staff on river water quality and help in the determination of pumping water to the reservoir. NOTE: nutrient data - phosphate, ammonia, and nitrate - are timestamped 30 minutes later from when the water was sampled.

institution: NOAA - National Weather Service - Central Region
title: Devil's Island, WI - Station DISW3
summary: DISW3 is a meteorological tower located on Devil's Island, Wisconsin in Lake Superior. Its site elevation is ~192 meters above sea level and the anemometer is 25 meters above site elevation. The station is owned and operated by NOAA's National Data Buoy Center.

institution: Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians
title: Dgowak (waves) Weather Buoy
summary: This buoy is located approximately three miles offshore of Sturgeon Bay Beach in Bliss, Michigan. The buoy, owned and operated by the Little Traverse Bay Band of Odawa Indians, will advance the understanding of near-shore waters, alert the public to hazardous conditions, protect water quality and improve weather forecasts. From about April 1 to Nov. 1 each year, the CB650 weather buoy will relay real-time information on wind speed, air and water temperature, wave height and direction, and other environmental characteristics such as: pH, DO, chlorophyl, turbidity, and conductivity.

title: Discovery World Panther Buoy
summary: DCW is a Panther buoy deployed in the embayment near Discovery World, Milwaukee, WI. It has been used to monitor water temperatures for the USA Triathlon. It is operated and maintained by University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.

title: Duluth-Nearshore Buoy(LLO1) : meteorological station
summary: In-situ buoy in Lake Superior north of Duluth, operated by the University of Minnesota-Duluth. The University of Minnesota, Duluth, with funding from the Great Lakes Observing System and the National Science Foundation, maintains two meteorological buoys. This one is roughly 10 miles northeast of Duluth, about a mile offshore of the McQuade Harbor.

title: Duluth-Offshore Buoy(LLO2) : meteorological station
summary: In-situ buoy in western Lake Superior, operated by the University of Minnesota-Duluth. The University of Minnesota, Duluth, with funding from the Great Lakes Observing System and the National Science Foundation, maintains two meteorological buoys. This one is roughly 10 miles northeast of Duluth, about ten miles offshore of the McQuade Harbor.

institution: State University of New York Buffalo State College
title: Dunkirk Buoy BSC1
summary: The information collected from this buoy, BSC1, can be used for climate modeling, lake current and energy budget modeling, as well as being useful for the study of nutrient dynamics and fisheries. The system is also useful for commercial and recreational navigation by providing real time information regarding wind and wave conditions. We would like to acknowledge the GLOS network for financial and technical support, we would also like to acknowledge the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation Lake Erie Fisheries Research Unit for assistance with anchor system deployment and retrieval.

title: East Grand Traverse Bay Sofar Mooring
summary: SPOT-1408 is a Sofar Spotter + Smart Mooring deployed in eastern Grand Travese Bay in Lake Michigan. It measures surface wave parameters, near surface water temperature, and provides derived wind information. It is owned and operated by Northwestern Michigan College. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Entrance Light, Green Bay Monitoring Station
summary: Water quality monitoring buoy located approximately 8.5 miles north of the mouth of the Fox River, Green Bay. Station established in 1986 as part of NEW Water's Aquatic Monitoring Program and was upgraded in 2021 to a buoy platform. Parameters are measured from 1 meter below the surface and 1 meter above the bottom of the water column. Top 1-m parameters include water temperature, conductivity, dissolved oxygen, pH, total algae, and turbidity. Bottom 1-m parameters include temperature, conductivity, dissolved oxygen, total algae and turbidity. NEW Water is the sole funding source.

title: Flood Dog Site 001
summary:
Flood Dog 001 (FD-001) provides sonic sensor-derived water levels and ambient air temperature every 15 minutes. This sensor is mounted to a pier at the Queen City Yacht Club in Toronto, Ontario and is operated by the community science group Flood Dog Co.

On March 15, 2022 a reference elevation of 1.116 meters above the water line was recorded. Calibrated to the www.tides.gc.ca Toronto Station #13320 (75.1 meters above sea level at a distance ~1.5km away) the FD-001 sensor was calculated to be 76.13 meters above sea level.

Current water surface elevation is calculated from the known sensor height Z (76.13m) minus the current raw observation Z'. For example a Z' reading of .75 meters from the sensor derives a lake water level of 76.13 - .75 meters above sea level; the “surface elevation” of the water is thus 75.38 meters above sea level.

title: Foster Ave.., Chicago, IL Weather Station
summary: The weather station at Foster Beach Park Park on Foster Ave in Chicago, IL (USA) was established and is maintained by the Chicago Park District. The purpose is to provide real-time meteorological information to the public. The station measures temperature, winds, precipitation, and other weather parameters.

title: Fox River, Green Bay Water Quality Monitoring Station
summary: Water quality monitoring station located at the mouth of the Fox River, Green Bay. Station established in 1986 as part of NEW Water's Aquatic Monitoring Program and was upgraded in 2022 to stream data in near real time. Parameters are measured from 1 meter below the surface and 1 meter above the bottom of the water column. Top 1-m parameters include water temperature, conductivity, dissolved oxygen, pH, total algae, and phosphate. Bottom 1-m parameters include temperature, conductivity, dissolved oxygen, and turbidity. This station also measures the following weather parameter - wind speed, wind direction, air temperature. A grant from GLOS provided funding to bring this station online as well as fund Green Eyes NuLAB phosphate monitoring equipment. NEW Water is the long-term funding source.

title: GLERL Environmental Sample Processor 2
summary: An Environmental Sample Processor (ESP) is a "lab in a can" designed for autonomous deployment, meaning it can function on its own without human help once deployed. It collects water samples, concentrates particulate material, runs molecular diagnostics that are customized to the needs of the users, and sends data in near real-time.

title: GLERLWE13:Western Erie Nutrient Buoy
summary: NOAA GLERL\u2019s fieldwork in Lake Erie focuses on observing the size, movement, and toxicity of harmful algal blooms (HABs). Data is collected continuously with real time nutrient buoys in Lake Erie throughout the season. This work helps GLERL to quantify the influence of nutrients on HAB growth and toxicity, which supports NOAA in providing critical information to regional stakeholders via the Lake Erie HAB Forecast and the Experimental Lake Erie HAB Tracker tool.

title: GLOS Sofar Smart Mooring
summary: This Spotter buoy + Smart Mooring is owned by the Great Lakes Observing System and is operated by Michigan Technological University. It measures surface wave parameters, surface and bottom water temperatures, and provides derived wind information. SPOT-1127 has been deployed as both a drifting and moored buoy in 2021, with its most recent deployment being near Granite Island in Lake Superior as a moored buoy. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Grand Marais Spotter Buoy
summary: This Spotter V2 buoy is located four miles north of the harbor in Grand Marais, MI. It will be deployed from spring to early winter, and will collect important navigation and climate planning data including wave height, wind speed, water temperature and more. The live data provided by this buoy is critical for commercial and recreational boaters as well as the National Weather Service, Environment Canada and NOAA, and will be used for long term climate adaptation planning with coastal communities in the Upper Peninsula. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Granite Island:meterological station
summary: Granite Island is a 2.5-acre island in Lake Superior, roughly 12 miles north of Marquette in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan. The island is composed of granite rock and rises nearly 60 feet above the surface of Lake Superior. The lighthouse began operation in 1869, was automated in 1937, and then was privately purchased and restored by Scott and Martine Holman in 1999. In 2009 Dr. John Lenters, then an associate professor at the University of Nebraska-Lincoln, installed an eddy covariance system and weather station to measure lake evaporation and other atmospheric variables. In 2013 Northern Michigan University took ownership of the eddy covariance station, with LimnoTech helping to maintain the site.

title: Green Bay buoy (GB17) : meteorological and water quality data
summary: The Green Bay buoy (GB17) is located approximately 40 km northeast of the mouth of the Fox River in southern Green Bay. The CB-1500 coastal data buoy is secured by a two-point mooring system over a mud substrate in 13 meters of water. The buoy is equipped with a solar-powered weather station and surface and near-bottom water quality sensors that collect data every 30 min, as well as a cellular modem for real-time data communication. This dataset contains water quality data from a couple of surface sondes, EXO and C3, the latter of which has its parameters isolated in the 0 ft (or m) depth section on the Seagull dive deeper page.

title: Green Bay East (45184) :meteorological and water quality station
summary: Lower Green Bay is a dynamic transition zone between the blue waters of Lake Michigan and nutrient rich waters of the Fox River and Lake Winnebago pool (The Fox-Wolf Watershed). Nutrients and algal biomass deposited in the lower bay contribute to the formation of toxic algal blooms. These blooms can form and decay over short time scales and the environmental conditions under which blooms form in lower Green Bay are not well understood. The Green Bay East buoy provides real- time continuous monitoring of algal biomass and water quality conditions. This data serves as an early warning system for bloom activity and may help us to better understand environmental conditions under which blooms form in lower Green Bay.

title: HW Algonac
summary: This site is located the estuary of St. Clair River to Lake St. Clair. This site is one of the 14 source water intake points belonging to the Huron to Erie Drinking Water Monitoring Network established in 2007 along the U.S side of the Huron to Erie corridor. With real-time monitoring equipment including EXO2 and TD4100, etc., the network can automatically detect anomalies in source water and send notifications to all water treatment plants along the corridor for early warning.

title: Lake County East Sonde Monitoring Station
summary: The Lake County Department of Utilities (LCDU) East Sub-District WTP is located on Lake Road in Painesville Township OH and has a design capacity of 9 million gallons a day. The YSI EXO 2 Sonde is installed the treatment facilities raw water pumping station located on the Lake Erie shore line in the eastern portion of the county. This facility draws water from its 48 inch intake extends approximately 4,000 feet into Lake Erie. The LCDU is proud to support the GLOS monitoring network and to bring additional knowledge and value to the residents of Lake County.

title: Lake County West Sonde Monitoring Station
summary: The Lake County Department of Utilities (LCDU) West Sub-District Treatment Facility is located on Aquarius Parkway in the City of Willoughby and has a design capacity of 20 million gallons a day. The YSI EXO 2 Sonde is installed the treatment facilities raw water pumping station located on the Lake Erie shore line in the western portion of the county. This facility draws water from its 60 inch intake extends approximately 3,000 feet into Lake Erie. The LCDU is proud to support the GLOS monitoring network and to bring additional knowledge and value to the residents of Lake County.

institution: Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Conservation and Parks
title: Lake Erie Central Basin 1 - OMOECC Environmental Sensors
summary: OMECP is a seasonally deployed moored buoy in the central basin of Lake Erie near Port Glasgow, Ontario, Canada. The buoy in in ~18 meters of water and is equipped to measure  water quality and physical water parameters throughout the water column. The buoy is operated and maintained by the Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Conservation and Parks.

title: Lake Erie ESP
summary: An Environmental Sample Processor (ESP) is a "lab in a can" designed for autonomous deployment, meaning it can function on its own without human help once deployed. It collects water samples, concentrates particulate material, runs molecular diagnostics that are customized to the needs of the users, and sends data in near real-time.

title: Lake St. Clair Deep Water Buoy
summary: This location measures measures wind speed, wind direction,gust, relative humidity, barometric pressure, air temperature, dew point, precip, water temperature at 5 discrete depths, water surface temperature, incident long and short wave radiation, reflected long and short wave radiation, and wave parameters. The precipitation amount is the total amount since the sensor has been turned on,  while the precipitation rate is the intensity of rainfall over the last 60 minutes.

title: Les Cheneaux/Eastern Straits Sofar Smart Mooring SPOT-30114R
summary: SPOT-30114R is a Sofar Smart Mooring deployed two miles southeast of Marquette Island (MI) in northern Lake Huron. It is owned and maintained by the Great Lakes Research Center at Michigan Technological University and deployed with assistance of local stakeholders to enhance safety for area recreation, while providing valuable real-time observations for Great Lakes researchers and forecasters. The station is deployed approximately May 1 through November 1. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Les Cheneaux/Eastern Straits Spotter Buoy
summary: This buoy is located two miles southeast of Marquette Island (MI) in northern Lake Huron. The buoy is owned and maintained by the University of Michigan's Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research and deployed with the assistance of local stakeholders to enhance safety for area recreation, while providing valuable realtime observations for Great Lakes researchers and forecasters. Each year from about May 1 to November 1, this Sofar Smart Mooring will measure wave height and wave period, as well as temperature-at-depth information every 30 minutes, reporting these values once per hour. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Little Cedar Point: water quality station
summary: Researchers at the University's Lake Erie Center sensors monitor blue-green algae. Missions of the Center include researching environmental conditions in Maumee Bay and western Lake Erie as well as discerning linkages among land-use practices, water quality, habitat, economics, natural resources, sustainability, and environmental and public health. The UT HAB Buoy is sponsored by the Ohio Board of Regents and the University of Toledo and collects water quality data.

title: Little Presque Isle Sofar Spotter Buoy
summary: SPOT-1816 is a Sofar Spotter buoy deployed off of Little Presque Isle near Marquette, MI in Lake Superior. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

summary: Operated by Bruce Power and Nuclear Innovation Institute, this buoy tracks water temperature, water level, and wave height within the Bruce Power local study area (LSA). This project supports the Bruce Power Thermal Monitoring Program. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Mackinac Straits West Buoy : meteorological station
summary: The buoy at the Mackinac Straits West buoy station (NDBC Station 45175) is a Total Integrated Data Acquisition Systems (TIDAS) model S2 Yachts-900 marine research station equipped with an Acoustic Doppler Current Profiler. The buoy is removed each year during the winter months. As currently configured, the station collects wind direction, wind speed and gust speed, air and water surface temperatures, relative humidity, dew point, barometric pressure, solar radiation, significant wave height, dominant period of waves, wave direction, buoy battery voltage, and the depth and eastward and northward water velocities for each of 28 vertical bins of the water column.

title: Marquette Spotter Buoy
summary: This Spotter V2 buoy is located one half mile northeast of Presque Isle Park in Marquette, MI. It will be deployed from spring to early winter, and will collect important navigation and climate planning data including wave height, wind speed, water temperature and more. The live data provided by this buoy is critical for commercial and recreational boaters as well as the National Weather Service, Environment Canada and NOAA, and will be used for long term climate adaptation planning with coastal communities in the Upper Peninsula. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Mawickwe Bay Panther Buoy
summary: MBB is a Panther buoy deployed in Mawickwe Bay, Lake Superior. It is operated and maintained by University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee on a seasonal basis.

title: McGinty Cove (Isle Royale National Park)
summary: SPOT-1041 is a Sofar Spotter buoy + Smart Mooring deployed near McGinty Cove at Isle Royale National Park in Lake Superior. It measures surface wave parameters, surface and bottom water temperatures, and provides derived wind information. It is owned and operated by Michigan Technological University and is maintained in partnership with the National Park Service. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Mentor Wet Well:water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. Between 2014 and 2018, LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant system at Mentor- Aqua America to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system.This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

title: Michigan City Buoy: meterorological station
summary: This buoy is located three miles offshore of Michigan City, Indiana. The buoy, jointly owned and operated by Illinois-Indiana Sea Grant and the Purdue University Department of Civil Engineering, will advance the understanding of near-shore waters, alert the public to hazardous conditions, protect water quality and improve weather forecasts. From about April 1 to Nov. 1 each year, the TIDAS 900 buoy will relay real-time information on wind speed, air and water temperature, wave height and direction, and other environmental characteristics.

institution: NOAA - National Weather Service - Central Region
title: Munising Lake Shore, MI - Station KP53
summary: KP53is a meteorological tower near Munising, Michigan. The station is owned and maintained by NOAA's National Weather Service Central Region.

title: Munsing Spotter Buoy
summary: This Spotter V2 buoy is located five miles north of Miners Castle, Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore in Munising, MI.  It will be deployed from spring to early winter, and will collect important navigation and climate planning data including wave height, wind speed, water temperature and more.  The live data provided by this buoy is critical for commercial and recreational boaters as well as the National Weather Service, Environment Canada and NOAA, and will be used for long term climate adaptation planning with coastal communities in the Upper Peninsula. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

institution: Chippewas of Nawash Unceded First Nation (CNUFN)
title: Nearshore Georgian Bay Sofar Smart Mooring
summary: This buoy is operated by the Chippewas of Nawash Unceded First Nation Fisheries Assessment Program to track water temperatures in the nearshore area during key seasonal windows. This deployment supports several research projects regarding fish species of cultural and socioeconomic importance to the Saugeen Ojibway Nation. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Neenah Drinking Water Intake Buoy
summary: Neenah is a seasonally deployed moored buoy in Lake Winnebago, Wisconsin, USA. It is positioned near the drinking water intake for the Neenah Water Utility and is equipped to measure water quality including algal blooms, as well as meteorological parameters and temperature throughout the water column. The buoy was built and is operated and maintained by University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.

institution: NOAA Office of National Marine Sanctuaries
title: Neshotah Park, WI Shipwreck Sanctuary Weather Station
summary: NESHOTAH is a combination weather and webcam station located at Neshotah Park, in Two Rivers, Wisconsin. The station is located within the Wisconsin Shipwreck Coast National Marine Sanctuary. It is deployed and maintained in partnership with NOAA Sanctuaries, MTU"s Great Lakes Research Center, the city of Two Rivers, and SwimSmart.

institution: NOAA Office of National Marine Sanctuaries
title: Neshotah Park, WI SPOT-1275
summary: Funded via a grant from the Great Lakes Observing System, this data buoy is maintained by the Wisconsin Shipwreck Coast National Marine Sanctuary in cooperation with NOAA's Great Lakes Environmental Research Lab, the Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research, and Michigan Technological University. The buoy provides real-time wind and wave information. The data helps make on-water recreation safer, provides anglers with key water temperature information, and improves modeling and forecasting. Located off Neshotah Park in Two Rivers, WI, the buoy is active from approximately May 1 to November 1 each year. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Neshotah Park, WI, USA Spotter Buoy
summary: SPOT-1814 is a Sofar Spotter buoy deployed at Neshotah Park, WI, USA. It measures surface wave parameters, near surface water temperature, and provides derived wind information. It is owned and operated by Michigan Technological University.

title: North Central Lake Winnebago Buoy
summary: The North Central Lake Winnebago Buoy (NCWB) is deployed in Wisconsin's largest inland lake, Lake Winnebago, which eventually flows into lower Green Bay and then into Lake Michigan. The lake is a shallow system that experiences seasonal algal blooms, which serves as one of the drivers for this moored buoy. The buoy also monitors meteorological conditions, temperature profiles, and selected water quality parameters. NCWB is deployed in 3 meters of water and utilizes cellular communication for real-time data transmission. NCWB is funded by University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee with deployment support from the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources.

title: North Entry Buoy, North Keweenaw Peninsula : meteorological station
summary: 45023 is an in-situ buoy deployed in Lake Superior near the North entrance to the Keweenaw Peninsula. It is operated by Michigan Tech - Great Lakes Research Center and has been seasonally deployed since ~2011. The buoy was completely refurbished in 2024, including a new buoy platform and sensors, with partial support from the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law.

title: North Lake Huron NDBC Buoy
summary: Station 45003 is owned and operated by NOAA's National Data Buoy Center. 45003 is the north Lake Huron buoy located northeast of Alpena, MI in 135 meters of water. It is a 2.3 meter foam discus buoy that is seasonally deployed to monitor physical water and meteorological parameters.

title: North Lake Huron Spotter
summary: SPOT-1816, located near NDBC buoy 45003, is a Sofar Spotter buoy that is deployed in northern Lake Huron overwinter to help fill the wintertime observing gap. title: Oak Orchard Nearshore Monitoring Buoy
summary: Nearshore buoy deployed from May through October along the southern shore of Lake Ontario. The buoy consists of a yellow six foot diameter, dense foam float with a mast that extends approximately nine feet (~3 m) above the water surface. Temperature chains hang from the buoy extending from the surface to the lake bottom with temperature probes spaced at one meter (~3 ft) intervals. The buoy includes meteorological instruments to measure air temperature, relative humidity, wind speed and direction, barometric pressure, and solar radiation. The buoy is owned by the State University of New York College of Environmental Science and Forestry(SUNY ESF) and operated under the Great Lakes Research Consortium (GLRC) by the Upstate Freshwater Institute (UFI).

The purpose is to provide real-time meteorological information to the public. The station measures temperature, winds, precipitation, and other weather parameters.

title: Oregon Pump Station:water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. Between 2014 and 2018, LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant system at City of Oregon to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system.This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

summary: The Stone Lab Algal & Water Quality Lab allows researchers to identify plankton, measure chlorophyll content and cyanobacteria toxins, analyze organic and inorganic suspended solids, and test for nutrients such as phosphorus and nitrogen.This buoy helps Stone Lab staff monitor water conditions, including harmful algal blooms, in Lake Erie\u2019s western basin.

title: Oswego
summary: Nearshore buoy deployed from May through October, as well as over winter along the southern shore of Lake Ontario. The buoy consists of a yellow six foot diameter, dense foam float with a mast that extends approximately nine feet (~3 m) above the water surface. Temperature chains hang from the buoy extending from the surface to the lake bottom with temperature probes spaced at one meter (~3 ft) intervals. The buoy includes meteorological instruments to measure air temperature, relative humidity, wind speed and direction, barometric pressure, and solar radiation. A water quality datasonde is deployed near the surface from the Oswego buoy. The data sonde measures water temperature, specific conductivity, turbidity and chlorophyll-a. The overwinter monitoring system consists of instrumentation (T-String, wave and water current meter) and data logger deployed on the bottom of Lake Ontario, approximately 1.75 miles off the shore of Oswego, NY in 22 m of water.  At the lake's surface, a cellular modem antenna is installed on a modified winter buoy (winter stick) to provide telemetry to shore. The buoy is owned by the State University of New York College of Environmental Science and Forestry(SUNY ESF) and operated under the Great Lakes Research Consortium (GLRC) by the Upstate Freshwater Institute (UFI).

title: Ottawa County:water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. Between 2014 and 2018, LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant system at Ottawa County to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system.This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

institution: Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians
title: Petoskey State Park Weather Station
summary: This weather station is located at Petoskey State Park Bay Beach in Petoskey, Michigan. The weather station, owned and operated by the Little Traverse Bay Band of Odawa Indians, will gather more temporally robust, accurate, and precise measures of climatology to determine the effect of climatology on YOY Lake Whitefish recruitment, alert the public to hazardous conditions, and improve weather forecasts. Each year, the WS700 multi-parameter weather station will relay real-time information on wind speed and direction, air temperature, and other environmental characteristics such as: humidity, solar radiation, pressure, and precipitation.

title: Port Sheldon Buoy(45029): meteorological and water station
summary: The Port Sheldon buoy(45029) is located in Lake Michigan between Grand Haven and Holland. This buoy is owned and maintained by LimnoTech and is funded by contributions from local organizations, businesses and individuals. The buoy measures meteorological and water surface conditions like wind speed and direction, air and water temperature, relative humidity, wave direction, height and perio . The data is logged internally as well as transmitted in ten minute intervals to the internet via cellular modem.

institution: NOAA Office of National Marine Sanctuaries
title: Port Washington, WI Spotter Buoy
summary: Funded via a grant from the Great Lakes Observing System, this data buoy is maintained by the Wisconsin Shipwreck Coast National Marine Sanctuary in cooperation with the Great Lakes Environmental Lab and Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research. The buoy provides real time wind and wave information, as well as temperature through the water column. The data helps make on-water recreation safer, provides anglers with key water temperature information, and improves modeling and forecasting. Located off Port Washington, WI, the buoy is active from approximately May 1 to November 1 each year. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Put-in Bay: water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant system at Village of Put-in Bay to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system.This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

title: Radiatively-driven convection buoy for the National Science Foundation (RDC_NSF)
summary: RDC_NSF is a moored buoy in southwest Lake Superior off of Grand Marais used to study radiatively driven convection. It started collecting data on 20 April 2021 as part of a 3-year National Science Foundation funded proposal. It was used to study surface heat and momentum fluxes from approximately April to July by measuring basic meteorological parameters, as well as surface water temperature and turbidity. The buoy is operated and maintained by University of Minnesota-Duluth's Large Lake Observatory.

title: RAEON-UWSS-006 Sensor Line
summary: This station is part of an array comprised of 3 stations. The purpose of this station is to monitor water quality and temperatures near the UWSS (Union Water Supply Systems) water intake. The station is maintained by the Real-Time Aquatic Ecosystem Observation Network (RAEON) at the University of Windsor. This station was established in 2021 and operated from May through November.

title: RAEON-UWSS-006 Water Intake Station
summary: This station is part of  an array comprised of 3 stations. The purpose of this station is to monitor meteorological parameters and nitrate concentrations near the Union Water Supply System (UWSS) water intake. The station is maintained by the Real-Time Aquatic Ecosystem Observation Network (RAEON) at the University of Windsor. This station was established in 2021 and operated from May through November.

title: Salmon Unlimited, WI Buoy
summary: 45199 is a moored buoy located off of Racine, WI in Lake Michigan in ~40 m of water. The buoy is equipped to measure waves, currents, and temperature, as well as meteorological parameters. The buoy is owned and operated by Salmon Unlimited of Wisconsin and is maintained in partnership with University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.

title: Sandusky Bay Bridge
summary: The Sandusky Bay Edison Bridge station was installed to monitor water quality as well as current speed of the water moving from Sandusky Bay into Lake Erie

title: Sandusky Bay Buoy (BGSUSD)
summary: BGSUSD is a NexSens buoy deployed at the Sandusky Bay Island Water Works Intake. It provides continuous in-situ observations of meteorological and water surface conditions.

title: Sandusky Bay buoy:water quality station
summary: The dataset is provided by an YSI EXO-2 water quality sonde installed on a buoy East of the Edison Bridge bisecting Sandusky Bay. The sonde measures parameters important in tracking the intensity of a persistent Planktothrix harmful algal bloom.The purpose of the dataset is to provide a continuous dataset tracking the cyanobacterial bloom in Sandusky Bay. The bloom produces the hepatotoxin microcystin, and measuring the intensity of the bloom will assist in developing models that can help predict bloom intensity.

title: Sandusky Bayside Water Intake (BGSDB)
summary: BGSSB is a buoy deployed at the Sandusky Bayside Water Intake. It provides continuous in-situ observations ofwater surface conditions.

institution: National Center for Water Quality Research at Heidelberg University
title: Sandusky River Station at the National Center for Water Quality Research
summary: This sonde is located at the National Center for Water Quality Research's (NCWQR) Sandusky River station south of Fremont, Ohio. The sonde owned and operated by the NCWQR will provide access to real-time water quality data for dissolved oxygen, temperature, specific conductivity, turbidity, chlorophyll and phycocyanin, as well as NICO nitrate.

title: Sandusky Subbasin Buoy:water quality station
summary: The Stone Lab Algal & Water Quality Lab allows researchers to identify plankton, measure chlorophyll content and cyanobacteria toxins, analyze organic and inorganic suspended solids, and test for nutrients such as phosphorus and nitrogen.This buoy was donated to the lab by  Fondriest Environmental and upgraded with additional equipment through grant funding helps Stone Lab staff monitor water conditions, including harmful algal blooms, in Lake Erie\u2019s western basin.

title: Sandusky Water Intake:water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. Between 2014 and 2018, LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant system at Sandusky Water Intake to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system.This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

institution: NOAA - National Weather Service - Central Region
title: Saxon Harbor, WI - Station SXHW3
summary: SXHW3 is a meteorological tower located in Saxon Harbor, Wisconsin. Its site elevation is 184 meters above sea level and the anemometer is 10 meters above site elevation. The station is owned and operated by NOAA's National Weather Service Central Region.

title: SBSK Point Betsie Spotter Buoy
summary: This buoy is located 5 miles north of Point Betsie (MI) in northern Lake Michigan. The buoy is owned and maintained by the University of Michigan's Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research and deployed with the assistance of local stakeholders to enhance safety for area recreation, while providing valuable realtime observations for Great Lakes researchers and forecasters. Each year from about May 1 to November 1, this Sofar Smart Mooring will measure wave height and wave period, as well as temperature-at-depth information every 30 minutes, reporting these values once per hour.

title: SBSK Point Betsie Spotter Buoy
summary: This buoy is located 5 miles north of Point Betsie (MI) in northern Lake Michigan. The buoy is owned and maintained by the University of Michigan's Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research and deployed with the assistance of local stakeholders, including Sleeping Bear Surf & Kayak, to enhance safety for area recreation, while providing valuable realtime observations for Great Lakes researchers and forecasters. Each year from about May 1 to November 1, this Sofar Spotter Buoy will measure wave height and wave period every 30 minutes, reporting these values once per hour. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

institution: NOAA Office of National Marine Sanctuaries
title: Sheboygan, WI Spotter Buoy
summary: Funded via a grant from the Great Lakes Observing System, this data buoy is maintained by the Wisconsin Shipwreck Coast National Marine Sanctuary in cooperation with the Great Lakes Environmental Lab and Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research. The buoy provides real time wind and wave information, as well as temperature through the water column. The data helps make on-water recreation safer, provides anglers with key water temperature information, and improves modeling and forecasting. Located off Sheboygan, WI, the buoy is active from approximately May 1 to November 1 each year. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Sodus Point Nearshore Monitoring Buoy
summary: A 2.0 m diameter disc buoy (YSI EMM 2.0) is deployed in Lake Ontario near Sodus Point, NY at the 7 m isopleth during the summer months June -- September. The buoy is outfitted with a meterological station that measures air temperature, relative humidity, wind speed and direction, and solar radiation. A temperature string with sensors at one meter intervals measure water temperature from the surface to 6 m. A YSI 6600 data sonde with temperature, specific conductivity, and turbidity is positioned ~1 m below the surface. A YSI 6600 data sonde with temperature, specific conductivity, and turbidity sensors is positioned ~1 m below the surface. An ADCP is deployed on the bottom ~30 m horizontal distance from the surface buoy. The ADCP (Nortek AWAC) measures water velocity and wave height and direction. These data are retrieved by a shore station every 15 to 30 minutes.

title: South Entry Buoy, South Keweenaw Peninsula: meteorological station
summary: 45025 is an in-situ buoy deployed in Lake Superior near the South entrance to the Keweenaw Peninsula. It is operated by Michigan Tech - Great Lakes Research Center and has been seasonally deployed since ~2011. The buoy was completely refurbished in 2024, including a new buoy platform and sensors, with partial support from the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law.

title: South Haven Buoy(45168)
summary: The South Haven buoy(45168) is located in Lake Michigan near South Haven. This buoy is owned and maintained by LimnoTech and is funded through a NOAA Coastal Storms grant with ongoing support from the City of South Haven, Van Buren County, and Entergy \u2013 Palisades Nuclear Plant. The buoy measures meteorological and water surface conditions like wind speed and direction, air and water temperature, relative humidity, wave direction, height and perio . The data is logged internally as well as transmitted in ten minute intervals to the internet via cellular modem.

title: Spectacle Reef Light: Realtime Coastal Observation Network (ReCON) Station
summary: The Spectacle Reef eddy covariance and meteorological station is maintained by the University of Colorado-Boulder and located 28 miles east of Mackinaw City, Michigan on Lake Huron. The station is part of the Great Lakes Evaporation Network (GLEN), which was established to improve observations of over-lake meteorology and evaporation, to use these observations to provide more accurate projections of Great Lakes water levels, and to support a variety of stakeholders, including the National Weather Service (NWS), U.S. and Canadian Coast Guard, recreational boaters and commercial shipping, emergency management officials, and the Great Lakes research community.

title: Toledo Pump Station
summary: A part of Lake Eerie Harmful Algae Blooms Monitoring network, this data is coming from the Toledo low service pump station, Ohio. The station collects water quality data like BGA, Chlorophyll, dissolved oxygen matter and turbidity.

title: Toledo Water Intake Buoy
summary: Lake conditions (weather, waves, water quality, algae) near the water intake for the Collins Park Water Treatment Plant are continuously monitored to inform water treatment plant operators of any potential harmful algal bloom (HAB) formation. The City of Toledo Department of Public Utilities, Division of Water Treatment, supports this buoy.

title: Toledo Water Intake Crib
summary: A part of Lake Erie Harmful Algae Blooms Monitoring network, this data is coming from a sonde at the bottom of a Toledo Water Intake Crib buoy. The sonde measures water quality parameters like BGA, Chlorophyll and turbidity.

institution: NOAA Office of National Marine Sanctuaries
title: Two Rivers, WI Spotter Buoy
summary: Funded via a grant from the Great Lakes Observing System, this data buoy is maintained by the Wisconsin Shipwreck Coast National Marine Sanctuary in cooperation with the Great Lakes Environmental Lab and Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research. The buoy provides real time wind and wave information, as well as temperature through the water column. The data helps make on-water recreation safer, provides anglers with key water temperature information, and improves modeling and forecasting. Located off Two Rivers, WI, the buoy is active from approximately May 1 to November 1 each year. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

institution: NOAA Office of National Marine Sanctuaries
title: Two Rivers, WI Spotter Buoy
summary: Funded via a grant from the Great Lakes Observing System, this data buoy is maintained by the Wisconsin Shipwreck Coast National Marine Sanctuary in cooperation with the Great Lakes Environmental Research Lab, the Cooperative Institute for Great Lakes Research, and Michigan Technological University. The buoy provides real time wind and wave information, as well as temperature through the water column. The data helps make on-water recreation safer, provides anglers with key water temperature information, and improves modeling and forecasting. Located off Two Rivers, WI, the buoy is active from approximately May 1 to November 1 each year. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Vermont EPSCoR Meteorological station - Lake Champlain
summary: Data supplied is from a meteorological buoy deployed in the Inland Sea of Lake Champlain. It consists of standard meteorological observations (wind speed, wind direction, air temperature, humidity, incoming solar radiation, air pressure) as well as water temperatures at various depths within the water column, an Acoustic Doppler Current Profiler and 4 above-water cameras set up 90\u00b0 apart from each other. This meteorological station is used as a data resource for the 5-yr National Science Foundation funded Basin Response to Extreme Events (BREE) program at the University of Vermont.

title: Village of Marblehead:water quality station
summary: Monitoring lake conditions at water treatment plants, remote pump stations, and intakes are an effective Harmful Algae Blooms (\u201cHABs \u201c) early warning system. Between 2014 and 2018, LimnoTech and GLOS worked with the water treatment plant system at Village of Marblehead to bring online the first version of the Lake Erie HABs monitoring network (the \u201cLake Erie HABs EWS\u201d). In 2017, GLOS, together with Cleveland Water Alliance, LimnoTech, NOAA GLERL and Ohio State University, embarked on a 3-year project funded by the NOAA Ocean Technology Transition project to transition the Lake Erie HABs EWS into a sustainable, operational system.This allows water managers and researchers in the Lake Erie region to have timely and easy access to critical monitoring data during future blooms to help them make informed decisions about activities and resources affected by HABs presence and toxicity.

title: Washington Island Spotter Buoy
summary: This buoy is located off the southwest coast of Washington Island, Wisconsin in Lake Michigan. The buoy is owned, maintained, and deployed by Michigan Technological University's Great Lakes Research Center to enhance safety for recreational stakeholders, while providing valuable realtime observations for Great Lakes researchers and forecasters. Each year from about May 1 to November 1, this Sofar Smart Mooring will measure wave height and wave period, as well as surface temperature every 30 minutes, reporting these values once per hour. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Washington Island Spotter Buoy
summary: This buoy is located off the southwest coast of Washington Island, Wisconsin in Lake Michigan. The buoy is owned, maintained, and deployed by Michigan Technological University's Great Lakes Research Center to enhance safety for recreational stakeholders, while providing valuable realtime observations for Great Lakes researchers and forecasters. Each year from about May 1 to November 1, this Sofar Smart Mooring will measure wave height and wave period, as well as surface temperature every 30 minutes, reporting these values once per hour. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

title: Washington Island, WI Sofar Smart Mooring
summary: SPOT-1384 is a Sofar Spotter buoy + Smart Mooring deployed near Washington Island in Door County, WI in Lake Michigan. It measures surface wave parameters, surface and bottom water temperature, and provides derived wind information. It is owned and operated by Michigan Technological University and is maintained in partnership with Washington Island Ferry Line. NOTE: The wind values displayed for these buoys (Sofar Spotters & Smart Moorings) are based on an estimate from its wave measurements, and not an actual direct measurement.

institution: University of Illinois - Illinois State Geological Survey
title: Waukegan coastal monitoring buoy
summary: Buoy 45186 (Waukegan) is owned by the Illinois State Geological Survey (ISGS), a division of the Prairie Research Institute at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. Annual operational cost is provided by the Illinois Department of Natural Resources Coastal Management Program (Illinois CMP). The buoy was built and first deployed by LimnoTech, Inc., in 2018. The startup cost for purchase and initial deployment was possible through a grant award to Illinois CMP and ISGS from NOAA, Office of Coastal Management. LimnoTech, Inc. continues to service, deploy, and retrieve the buoy annually though a cooperative effort with the ISGS and Illinois CMP.

title: West Lake Erie NDBC Buoy
summary: Station 45005 is owned and operated by NOAA's National Data Buoy Center. 45005 is the west Lake Erie buoy located northwest of Lorain, OH in 9.8 meters of water. It is a 2.4 meter discus buoy that is seasonally deployed to monitor physical water and meteorological parameters.

title: West Lake Superior NDBC Buoy
summary: Station 45006 is owned and operated by NOAA's National Data Buoy Center. 45006 is the west Lake Superior buoy located northeast of Outer Island, Wisconsin in 195 meters of water. It is a 2.3 meter foam discus buoy that is seasonally deployed to monitor physical water and meteorological parameters.

institution: Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Conservation and Parks
title: Western Lake Erie 2 - OMECP Environmental Sensors
summary: OMECP_E2 is a seasonally deployed moored buoy in the western basin of Lake Erie near Leamington, Ontario, Canada. The buoy is in ~10 meters of water and is equipped to measure water quality and physical water parameters. The buoy is operated and maintained by the Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Conservation and Parks.

institution: Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Conservation and Parks
title: Western Lake Ontario 1 - OMECP Environmental Sensors
summary: Western Lake Ontario 1 is a real-time water quality data system consisting of a buoy and benthic unit deployed by the Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Conservation and Parks (OMECP) in Lake Ontario. The system is located ~2 km offshore of Ajax, ON in ~20 m of water and is used to monitor nearshore water quality conditions at the surface and bottom.

institution: Ontario Ministry of the Environment, Conservation and Parks
title: Western Lake Ontario 2 - OMECP Environmental Sensors
summary: Western Lake Ontario 2 is real-time water quality data system consisting of a buoy, benthic unit and mid-depth nodes deployed by the Ontario Ministry of the Environment and Climate Change (OMOECC) in Lake Ontario. The system is located ~2 km offshore of Etobicoke, ON in ~20 m of water and is used to monitor nearshore water quality conditions at the surface, bottom, 5 m off bottom and 11 m off bottom within the water column.

institution: Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians
title: Wildnerness State Park Weather Station
summary: This weather station is located at Wilderness State State Park Bay Beach in Carp Lake, Michigan. The weather station, owned and operated by the Little Traverse Bay Band of Odawa Indians, will gather more temporally robust, accurate, and precise measures of climatology to determine the effect of climatology on YOY Lake Whitefish recruitment, alert the public to hazardous conditions, and improve weather forecasts. Each year, the WS700 multi-parameter weather station will relay real-time information on wind speed and direction, air temperature, and other environmental characteristics such as: humidity, solar radiation, pressure, and precipitation.

institution: Illinois-Indiana Sea Grant and Purdue University
title: Wilmette Buoy: meteorological station
summary: This buoy is located roughly four miles off the coast of Wilmette, Ill., relays information on wind speed, air and water temperature, wave height and direction, and other environmental characteristics from May to October each year. Owned and maintained by Illinois-Indiana Sea Grant and Purdue Civil Engineering.

institution: University of Illinois - Illinois State Geological Survey
title: Winthrop Harbor Buoy
summary: Buoy 45187 (Winthrop Harbor) is owned by the Illinois State Geological Survey (ISGS), a division of the Prairie Research Institute at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. Annual operational cost is provided by the Illinois Department of Natural Resources Coastal Management Program (Illinois CMP). The buoy was built and first deployed by LimnoTech, Inc., in 2018. The startup cost for purchase and initial deployment was possible through a grant award to Illinois CMP and ISGS from NOAA, Office of Coastal Management. LimnoTech, Inc. continues to service, deploy, and retrieve the buoy annually though a cooperative effort with the ISGS and Illinois CMP.

title: Wisconsin Point Buoy 45217 from the Lake Superior NERR
summary: 45217, or LKSWIWQ, is a water quality monitoring buoy located in nearshore Lake Superior near Wisconsin Point, within the Lake Superior National Estuarine Research Reserve. It was initially deployed in 2024 and is typically deployed May through October. This station was established with support from the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law.
